White Wine Analysis by David DeSimone

In this project, I will be looking at thousands of white wines that have been judged and given a rating between 0(bad) and 10(good). The wines were judged on 11 factors, such as acidity, sugar, sulfur dioxide, pH, and alcohol content. My goal is to determine which, if any, of these factors are most important in determining a wine’s rating and how they correlate with each other and the judged quality of the wines.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 4,898 white wines in this dataset. There are 12 variables (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality). Most of the variables follow a normal distribution pattern (aside form alcohol), and the numbers in the data are self explainatory.

Some interesting thigs to note:

  • There were no ratings lower than a 3, and no perfect 10’s. 9’s were also rare, with a count of 5.
  • The distribution of alcohol content is noticably flatter than the rest of the variables and is skewed to the right.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of the dataset is quality. I am mostly interested how the other variables directly affect perceived quality or interact with each other to affect perceived quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I might also pay special attention to certain variables which are also easy for an observer to pick up on – things like sugar and alcohol content. Of course, this is only an assumption, and I may find out that, while interesting, they have no effect on quality. Also, I may be surprised to find that variables that observers are oblivious to are affecting perceived quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created buckets for both sugar and alcohol. These will be used in later analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of data? If so, why did you do this?

I did log transform the alcohol and sugar variables to better represent their longer right tail. I also cut out big outliers on a couple of the variables in order to get a better look at the bulk of the data for the given variable.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9871  0.9917  0.9937  0.9940  0.9961  1.0390

This chart may reveal one of the most interesting findings yet. Wines with relatively low sugar content for a given density tend to have a lower quality. Wines with a higher sugar content at a given density have a higher quality. This is especially interesting because, individually, they have negative correlations with quality.

Here we can see how alcohol and density fit together to affect quality. We should expect top wines to fall at the upper left and poor wines at the lower right. # Multivariate Analysis

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Quality is the most important variable and is one of the few variables that, alone, we know we need to care about. Quality is the assumed to be determined by the combination of the other variables.

Plot Two

Description Two

Alcohol has the highest correlation to quality of all the variables. This boxplot helps us more easily see this correlation. Interestingly, wines with ratings of 3 and 4 don’t fall into the trend, but they still have lower alcohol than anything with a 6 or above rating.

Plot Three

Description Three

Density had the second highest correlation(inverse) to quality. It is interesting to see how strong the effect is when density is paired with alcohol. We can see some synergy between the two, but it doesn’t knock us off of our feet. Some of the highest rated wines are where we would least expect.

Reflection

This dataset was composed of 12 measurable variables and one subjective variable(quality – which is most important). Most variables had a normal distribution pattern, the standouts being residual sugar and alcohol. This was interesting because we know that both variables are discernible by human judges, and we know that people might have different preferences in these two areas. Through the analysis, we saw that alcohol and density were really the only two variables with a notable effect on quality. A few of the input variables had high correlations with each other, but I couldn’t attribute them to the final quality score.

While this was a big, clean data set with plenty of variables, the value of using these variables to measure quality is highly questionable. First of all, we don’t know which of these variables are detectable to the human senses. We could argue that the variables that have negligible correlation to quality are useless because quality is completely subjective and is the only variable that we truely care about! Also, there could be other factors that have significant effects on quality but were not measured in this study(something like flavor notes). We don’t know if the testers knew the price of these wines or were influenced by the bottle label. If there are not any other valuable measures that significantly predict quality of the wine, perhaps we should remember that wine quality is highly dependent on personal opinion. One person’s top wine is another’s bottom.
